Hi,

please note that a 'constrained network' is not the same as a
'constrained node network' according to [1] and NEWEST is now moving
from 'constrained node networks' to 'constrained networks'.

The original charter text talked about constrained node networks and
if that was by intention, we should use a wording like this:

  6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node
  networks, i.e., networks whose characteristics are influenced by
  being composed of a significant portion of constrained nodes. A
  constrained node is a node where some of the characteristics that
  are otherwise pretty much taken for granted for Internet nodes in
  2013 are not attainable.

[1] draft-ietf-lwig-terminology-05.txt

/js

