> >please note that a 'constrained network' is not the same as a
> >'constrained node network' according to [1] and NEWEST is now moving
> >from 'constrained node networks' to 'constrained networks'.
> >
> >The original charter text talked about constrained node networks and
> >if that was by intention, we should use a wording like this:
> >
> >   6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node
> >   networks, i.e., networks whose characteristics are influenced by
> >   being composed of a significant portion of constrained nodes. A
> >   constrained node is a node where some of the characteristics that
> >   are otherwise pretty much taken for granted for Internet nodes in
> >   2013 are not attainable.
> >
> >[1] draft-ietf-lwig-terminology-05.txt
> >
> >/js
> >
> >On Wed, Aug 28, 2013 at 03:37:42AM -0500, Timothy J. Salo wrote:
> >>How about:
> >>>=============
> >>>OLD:
> >>>6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node
> >>>networks, as defined in section 2.1. and 2.2. of
> >>>draft-ietf-lwig-terminology.
> >>>
> >>>NEW:
> >>>6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node
> >>>networks, using the following definitions:
> >>>   -  Constrained Node:  A node where some of the characteristics that
> >>>are otherwise pretty much taken for granted for Internet nodes in 2013
> >>>are not attainable, often due to cost constraints and/or physical
> >>>constraints on characteristics such as size, weight, and available power
> >>>and energy.
> >>>   -  Constrained Network:  A network where some of the characteristics
> >>>pretty much taken for granted with link layers in common use in the
> >>>Internet by 2013, are not attainable.
> >>NEWEST:
> >>6lo focuses on INT-area work that is needed for constrained networks,
> >>those in which certain resources are severely limited, such as
> >>bandwidth, computational power, storage, power, or energy.
> >>
> >>- - - - - - - - - - - - -
> >>
> >>Note: I don't think that we really care about, for example, size and
> >>weight constraints, except to the extent that these limitations affect
> >>the amount of things we care about (e.g., bandwidth, computational
> >>power, storage, ...).  That is, I suggest that we talk about only the
