A couple more suggested tweaks:

1. For completeness we also include the definition of "Constrained node=20
network" from draft-ietf-lwig-terminology-05:

Constrained Node Network:  A network whose characteristics are=20
influenced by being composed of a significant portion of constrained node=
s.

2. Use the term "constrained node networks" as the target for the WG,=20
with the implication this refers to constrained nodes and constrained=20
networks as defined.

So here is the suggested complete OLD/NEW charter text, based on=20
http://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/charter-ietf-6lo/ as written and=20
bracketed by <charter text></charter text>:

<charter text>
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D
OLD:
6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node=20
networks, as defined in section 2.1. and 2.2. of=20
draft-ietf-lwig-terminology. Specifically, it will work on:

1. IPv6-over-foo specifications using 6LoWPAN technologies (RFC4944,=20
RFC6282, RFC6775) for link layer technologies of interest in constrained =

node networks

2. Related MIBs

3. Common infrastructure specifications, such as header compression,=20
specific to constrained node networks

NEW:
6Lo focuses on INT area work that is needed for constrained node=20
networks, using the following definitions:

   -  Constrained Node:  A node where some of the characteristics that=20
are otherwise pretty much taken for granted for Internet nodes in 2013=20
are not attainable, often due to cost constraints and/or physical=20
constraints on characteristics such as size, weight, and available power =

and energy.
