On Aug 29, 2013, at 18:21, Brian Haberman <brian@innovationslab.net> =
wrote:

> Is it possible to scope the work using a definition of 6LoWPAN rather =
than the definitions in the LWIG draft?  Adrian holds a DISCUSS on the =
LWIG draft because of the scoping of those definitions.  He proposed =
that the 6lo charter avoid those definitions by scoping its work based =
on some 6LoWPAN description/definition.

The narrow definition of 6LoWPAN is that of "IP-over-foo for IEEE =
802.15.4".  We can't use that.

The wider explanation in the LWIG draft:

   One interesting class of a constrained network often used as a
   constrained node network is the "LoWPAN" [RFC4919], a term inspired
   from the name of the IEEE 802.15.4 working group (low-rate wireless
   personal area networks (LR-WPANs)).  [...]
   Originally focused on IEEE 802.15.4, "LoWPAN" (or when used for IPv6,
   "6LoWPAN") is now also being used for networks built from similarly
   constrained link layer technologies [I-D.ietf-6lowpan-btle]
   [I-D.mariager-6lowpan-v6over-dect-ule] [I-D.brandt-6man-lowpanz].

So it refers back to "constrained", but without using the other =
definitions in the LWIG terminology.

Gr=FC=DFe, Carsten


