Hi Samita,

Comments inline.

To summarise: I think we are going around in circles re. "constrained"=20
terms and I support Ulrich's suggestion to copy the terms from=20
draft-ietf-lwig-terminology verbatim.

Robert

On 31/08/2013 02:14, Samita Chakrabarti wrote:
> Hi All,
>
> There have been a lot of discussion in the list and I am catching up wi=
th them.
>
> Here are some proposed text for the charter and some thoughts ( as per =
the following email  from Brian ) .
>
> CURRENT
>
>
>   6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node=

> networks, as the term is defined by the LWIG working group.
>
> NEW:
>
> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node N=
etworks. The constrained node networks have  limited functionality compar=
ed to the  common IP networks composed of line-powered and high-capacity =
devices. An example of constrained networks is IPv6 over IEEE 802.15.4(6L=
oWPAN).
> The constrained nodes can be characterized by many different categories=
 such as node capability, cost of networks, media constraints, regulatory=
 limits, bit-rates etc.
<RCC>I think we are going around in circles here. I support Ulrich's=20
suggestion to simply copy the definitions from=20
draft-ietf-lwig-terminology. On the basis that it is almost impossible=20
to provide a definitive objective statement about what a "constrained"=20
anything is, I think the terms in draft-ietf-lwig-terminology are well=20
considered and well qualified. Whilst the qualifications are dealt with=20
more in the LWIG WG, the charter states that there will be coordination=20
with LWIG, so I don't see what else needs to be done for this.</RCC>
>
>
> CURRENT
> 6Lo works on small, focused pieces of Internet Area work. 6Lo does not =
take on
> larger cross-layer efforts. The working group will continue to reuse ex=
isting
> protocols and mechanisms whenever reasonable and possible.
>
> QUESTION:  Would like to know what we mean by "small focused pieces of =
Internet Area work" ?
>
> Would it be better to say "6Lo will work on focused pieces of Internet =
Area for which the work already started
> on the IPv6-over-foo and provide generic guidelines for IPv6 running on=
 constrained link-layers".
<RCC>The suggested text seems to preclude starting work for other=20
as-yet-to-be-determined link layers applicable to constrained node=20
networks, which would not be the case, surely? "small, focused pieces of =

Internet Area work" is clear enough to me.</RCC>
>
> Will this group develop any work on provisioning of the constrained nod=
es? Gateway devices between Internet (IPv6) and  constrained networks?
> If so,  it would be good to clarify them.
<RCC>Given the statement regarding security and management, I would=20
think not</RCC>
>
> CURRENT:
> Security and management work that is not specific to the link layers be=
ing
> worked on is out of scope.
>
> QUESTION: Is it trying to say?
>
> Any new security and management work that is not specific to the constr=
ained link, is out of scope.
> This sentence is not clear to me.
<RCC>
I would rather not bring in another "constrained" term here. I think the =

sentence as it stands is OK - a possible change which may clarify would=20
be something like:

"Security and management work that is not specific to the link layers=20
under consideration is out of scope."
</RCC>
>
>
> The rest looks fine to me.
>
> Thanks,
> -Samita
